description: For sale in our St. Louis showroom is a beautiful sixth generation 1960 Cadillac Series 62 Convertible. The odometer reads 75,668, but the actual mileage is unknown. Options for this 1960 Cadillac Series 62 Convertible: AM Radio, Automatic Convertible Top, Hub Caps, Wide White Wall Radial Tires, Power Steering, Power Brakes, Power Driver's Seat, Seat belts, Leather Interior, and Power Windows. Powering this 60' Cadillac drop top is a 390 CID V8 that is matched to a 4 speed Hydra-Matic automatic transmission. This Series 62 is finished in the classic and desirable white exterior and red leather interior color combination. The power vinyl top is also white to match the exterior color perfectly. The Cadillac Series 62 was produced between 1940 to 1964, and was intended to replace the Cadillac Series 65. The 1960 Series 62 had more subtle styling cues than the previous 1959 model including less chrome trim, lower tailfins, and removal of pointed front bumper guards. Other changes were a full-width grille and front fender mounted turn signals. There were about 14,000 Cadillac Series 62 Convertibles produced in 1960, and cost between $4,800 and $5,400. Power windows and a power driver's seat were standard in the Series 62 convertibles, and they also featured Florentine leather upholstery. To view this 1960 Cadillac Series 62 Convertible in greater detail, including HD pictures and an HD video, visit www.GatewayClassicCars.com or our St. Louis showroom. description: Super sharp 72,ooo mile example finished in factory coded Ebony Black over Black! Factory air conditioning, full power accessories, Dunlop wide whitewall tires, and all original drivetrain! Hard to beat this year Cadillac design!Recently serviced and ready to enjoy! One can only imagine the stress for the Cadillac design team after the 1959 debuted to the public. To put such a remarkably original design on the showrooms across the country, then try to out due themselves again the following year! Although it is considered one of the most desired cars among Cadillac collectors today, the audacious 1959 model was a little too flamboyant for some buyers during the day. Its wild charisma wasnt for everyone, and may have turned many longtime Cadillac enthusiasts away from showrooms. The answer in 1960 was a milder and more subdued finned design to woe traditional buyers back. It could not have been a more timely decision, and the 1960 model now rivals several Cadillac designs as one of the most popular today! Advertised as Elegance in Motion, the softer design lines of the 1960 model was a way to put Cadillac back ahead of its competition. We are extremely excited to offer this 1960 Cadillac Series 62 Convertible that has been in the same, careful hands of the last owner for the last 23 years! It was cosmetically restored to stock specifications including its repainted factory Ebony Black (color code 10) exterior and Black interior (21) with white convertible top (original code 2- black)! It comes powered by its original, numbers matching 390ci-4bbl V8 engine that produces a factory rated 325hp and Hydra-Matic transmission. Options include factory air conditioning, signal-seeking AM radio with rear seat speaker & power antenna, 6-way power driver seat, Guide-Matic automatic headlight dimmer, power windows & convertible top, factory standard power steering & brakes, passenger visor vanity mirror, windshield washer with 3-speed wiper, heat/defrost, dual outside rearview mirrors, rear fender skirts, front & rear seatbelts, rubber interior floor mats, standard soft boot cover, full wheel disc covers and bias 4-ply Dunlop wide whitewall tires, all original E-Z Eye tinted glass including windshield, power trunk release & pull down, and more! This wonderful car appears to have been absolutely pampered by its loving former owners and shows only 72,600 miles on the odometer today. The exterior paint is exceptional to the eye along with the new convertible top! The fresh interior upholstery is all color correct and shows no visual wear or any use since completion. Upon arrival to the St Louis Car Museum, we elected to professionally rebuild the entire transmission, replace the engine oil & filter, completely rebuild the factory air conditioning system to put it into full working order, replace both rear exhaust mufflers, and give this Cadillac a complete ignition tune up. description: For sale in our St. Louis showroom is the ultimate 1970s luxury cruiser: a seventh generation 1978 Cadillac Eldorado. The odometer reads 37,057, which reflects the actual mileage of this beautiful Cadillac. Options for this 1978 Cadillac Eldorado include: Air Conditioning, AM/FM Radio, Cruise Control, Hub Caps, Power Brakes, Power Steering, Power Locks, Power Windows, Power Seats, Tilt/Telescopic Wheel, Ride Control, Seat Belts, Leather Interior, and White Wall Radial tires. Powering this 78' Eldorado is the numbers matching 425 CID V8. The original 3 speed automatic transmission shifts the power to the front wheels with ease. Yes, you read that correctly. In 1967, the Cadillac Eldorado began using a front wheel drive platform, and it remained in use until the end of its production run. The Cadillac Eldorado was a personal luxury car that was produced by Cadillac from 1953 to 2002, and spanned 10 generations. The seventh generation of the Cadillac Eldorado had a production run from 1971 to 1978. The seventh generation Eldorado grew 2 inches in body length and 6 inches in wheelbase length from its sixth generation predecessor. This 1978 Eldorado received a new coat of Cadillac Platinum Pearl in 2015, which looks fantastic, especially shimmering in the sunlight. The original white leather interior is in good condition. The pillow-top seats are still insanely comfortable, and are free from any rips, tears, or serious wear. description: Large original V8, spacious cabin, and darning angular styling â€“ what was once the top luxury vehicle for the '60s is now a vintage cruiser with all the right flair.  So when this 1969 Cadillac Eldorado is also so affordable, it's time to take notice.

The design lines of the sixth generation Eldorado are ones of legend.  It's a true statement of personal luxury with flowing details.  The extra long hood starts with a sharp middle point and  begins a crease line that runs uninterrupted to the doors and emphasizes the sporty kick-up on the rear quarter panels.  And the super-slick rear end was there to let you know the excess of the tailfin era was over, but this Cadillac still knew how to pay homage to its history.  Also, while you're checking out the rear, take a look at the bumper.  That chrome king is integrated into the design better than you can even get on a modern Cadillac.  And if its brightwork you like, the front bumper shines just as brilliantly.  You can see all of these details so well because of the level of care that has gone into this Caddy.  The sheetmetal looks amazing, and the doors still shut with authority.  And on top of this straight body is the original shade of Astral Blue that has the kind of gloss to highlight every crease so this Eldorado looks like a finely pressed suit.  The pristine blue vinyl top not only gives this coupe a very European color scheme, but also it gives you a preview of the interior.

Inside, you'll love how everything from the wood paneling on the door to the plushness of the carpets have defied the decades.  The driver's seat has been worn in a bit, but quite frankly, you probably wish you were this complete as you approach nearly half a century on this earth.  Plus, you get the kind of luxury that made these Cadillacs so special in 1969, and the kind of options that you would expect in a brand new car today.  This includes power seats, power windows, power locks, tilt steering wheel, rear defogger, the original AM/FM stereo, and provisions for automatic climate control. You sit behind the original Caddy three-spoke steering wheel and gaze at a clear gauge package.  And all the controls are centered around you, because this is built to be a personal luxury machine.  But on those days when you want to share the comfort with family and friends, the flat floor of the Eldorado means it really does offer relaxed seating for up to six total.

The 472 cubic-inch V8 fills the engine bay, because this was the era when Cadillac was a true master at offering big motors with big power.  And more than just being the original numbers-matching V8, you can really tell there has been proper care and maintenance over the years thanks to items like the fresh hoses and belts.  Plus, there has been a great eye to preservation as noted by all the factory decals still present under the hood.
